<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="216" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d216">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72111 H 58/9½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-28">
                                    <hi rend="italic">28 February, 1917</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: This, like Penfield’s
                                letter,<note n="93" xml:id="d216fn1">Penfield’s letter not
                                printed.</note> begins to bear the aspect of ancient history, but it
                            is out of the question to let such charges go uncontradicted, and this
                            is unquestionably the right answer. It seems to me complete, and ought
                            to make the persons who formulated the note of complaint ashamed of
                            themselves.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. W.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>